    "summary": "The Prague Spring was a brief period of political liberalization in Czechoslovakia from January to August 1968, initiated by Communist Party leader Alexander Dubček, who implemented reforms he described as \"socialism with a human face.\" Dubček loosened censorship, allowed greater freedom of assembly and speech, rehabilitated victims of Stalinist purges, and began decentralizing economic authority. The reforms inspired widespread public enthusiasm and intellectual ferment in Prague and beyond.\n\nThe Soviet Union and Warsaw Pact allies viewed the reforms as a dangerous precedent that might spread. On the night of August 20–21, 1968, forces from the Soviet Union, Poland, Hungary, Bulgaria, and East Germany invaded Czechoslovakia. The Czechoslovak military did not resist. Soviet tanks rolled into Prague while citizens confronted soldiers in the streets. The Warsaw Pact invasion was condemned internationally, including by several communist parties in Western Europe.\n\nDubček was taken to Moscow and ultimately forced to resign. The Brezhnev Doctrine, articulated in the aftermath, asserted the Soviet Union's right to intervene in any socialist country where socialism was deemed threatened. Czechoslovakia returned to orthodox communist rule, and the reforms were systematically reversed in a process called normalization. The Prague Spring is remembered as a pivotal episode of the [[event:113|Cold War]], demonstrating both the aspirations for democratic socialism and the limits the Soviet Union would enforce.",
